channel.title: Intel Core 2 Duo E8600 Breaks the 6 GHz
channel.description:
Another good story from the Chinese website Coolaler.com. It brings along some good news for the Intel followers. Intel's highest-clocked 45nm Wolfdale processor, the yet unreleased Core 2 Duo E8600 appears to have some great overclocking potential. Coupled with a DFI LP UT P35 motherboard, 4GB of DDR2 memory, single Radeon HD 4870 card, and liquid nitrogen (LN) cooling the E8600 CPU was able to reach 6146.9MHz (614x10). That compared to its default speed of 3.33GHz (333x10), and we might have a new dual core overclocking winner. According to the information available on the Net, when released the E8600 will cost somewhere between $266 and $299.
http://www.techpowerup.com/img/08-07-08/Intel_E8600_6_14GHz_CPU-Z_02.jpg http://www.techpowerup.com/img/08-07-08/Intel_E8600_6_14GHz_CPU-Z_01.jpg :eek: Just crazy.

item.title: Intel Core 2 Duo E8600 Breaks the 6 GHz
item.dc:creator: @xEnt xEnt
item.description:
@xEnt wrote:

Stop counting counting the number of cores for each Ghz, use its base Ghz and leave it at that. If you went around on a Q6600 saying o hi, my 9.6ghz (2.4 x 4) processor owns u, you’ll get laughed at.

E8600 on 45nm process is a good clock for 6ghz, except how stable/long will it last? I’ve seen E2180’s clocked at 7.5ghz so if were just upping our fsb’s to gain a higher clock, get some pics then gtfo… then it really means nothing.

FSB mhz * CPU Multiplier = final mhz

Afaik multiple cores are just for usage, look at Ghz as speed, having 2 cores wont give you 6ghz of speed, but 2x 3ghz. More cores are like ram in how it’s usage works, depending on the application… Pretend the CPU is at 90% usage on both cores, have 2 more cores(quad) would just make all them work at 45% usage. No speed difference.

Its just like when people say (oh 4gb will make ur computer faster than 2gbs) when really it wont if you are not using > 2gb in memory. They will stay exactly the same, and the other 2gb will come into play only when it’s needed. Well from what I’ve heard on vista its different.

Ghz vs cores is up to the user. E8400 vs Q6600 all depends what you’re using it for. Both same priced, E8400 @ 3.0ghz with only 2 cores, Q6600 @ 2.4ghz with 4 cores.

Gamers would choose the E8400, and many do for this fact because the more mhz you have the better you’re games will run (for now, since hardly any games use 4 cores) and Quad cores are for pretty much anything else.

item.description:
@Uriko wrote:

[quote=“gikid, post:1, topic:218967”][quote author=postmanpat9 link=topic=287590.msg2326279#msg2326279 date=1215713206]
The “10GHZ” processor is 4 cores at 2.5Ghz each so it still has a 2.5GHZ clock. The dual core i posted has 2 cores at 6Ghz each.
[/quote]

You guys are fucking dumb. That is not how multicore technology works. To figure out the equivelant speed of a multicore processor to one single core processor, the formula is this:

[size=16pt]x[sup]n[/sup][/size]

x = core speed
n = number of cores

For example if you have a dual core processor at 2.6GHz, you would do

[size=16pt]2.6[sup]2[/sup] = ~6.76 GHz[/size]

or in your case

[size=16pt]2.5[sup]4[/sup] = 39.0625 GHz[/size][/quote]i’m pretty sure it’s just two cores working at 2.6ghz…edit: (combined)
